items.title: json5.dump to stdout does not pretty-print
items.body:
If I use `json5.dump` with the `indent` parameter to write directly to stdout it does not pretty print. If I output to a file it works. This diverges from the behavior of `json.dump`.

Example program:

```python
import json
import json5
from sys import stdout

data = {
    'test': 3,
    'more': 'stuff'
}

stdout.write('json.dump: \n')
json.dump(data, stdout, indent=2)
stdout.write('\njson5.dump: \n')
json5.dump(data, stdout, indent=2)
stdout.write('\njson5.dumps: \n')
stdout.write(json5.dumps(data, indent=2))
stdout.write('\n')
```

Output:

```
json.dump: 
{
  "test": 3,
  "more": "stuff"
}
json5.dump: 
{"test": 3, "more": "stuff"}
json5.dumps: 
{
  test: 3,
  more: "stuff",
}
```

items.title: "ValueError: Circular reference detected." exception on json5.dumps call
items.body:
When I call `json5.dumps` on a previously loaded and modified object, I get the following exception:

```
ValueError: Circular reference detected.
```

My environment info:

- Ubuntu 19.04
- Python 3.7.3
- json5 0.8.5

Code to recreate the issue (I know there's a logical error since `REGION` is modified for both  `development` and `t`):

```
import json5

def demo():
    js_object_str = """{
      development: {
        REGION: "foo",
      },
      prod: {
        REGION: "baz"
      }
    }"""

    all_configs = json5.loads(js_object_str)

    new_config = all_configs["development"]
    new_config.update({"REGION": "bar"})
    all_configs["t"] = new_config

    print(all_configs)
    print(json5.dumps(all_configs))  # this causes the error

demo()
```

Workaround:
Import `from copy import deepcopy` and change `all_configs["t"] = new_config` to `all_configs["t"] = deepcopy(new_config)`.

items.title: Identifiers starting with a reserved keyword are treated as reserved keywords
items.body:
First of all, thank you for this great library!

I noticed that `dump()` puts quotes around identifiers that only start with a reserved keyword. For example: `internal_parameter` would be dumped as `"internal_parameter"`.

The issue seems to be in the regex that is created in `lib._is_reserved_word()`. Just appending `$` to the whole pattern so that it reads `_reserved_word_re = re.compile('|'.join(['break', ..., 'with']) + '$')` fixes it.

Recently upgraded to 0.5 in my app. Ran it and got an `ImportError`:

```
Traceback (most recent call last):
...
  File "/path/to/app/api.py", line 4, in <module>
    from json5 import loads
  File "/path/to/virtualenv/local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/json5/__init__.py", line 17, in <module>

  File "/path/to/virtualenv/local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/json5/tool.py", line 28, in <module>

  File "/path/to/virtualenv/local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/json5/lib.py", line 19, in <module>
    from builtins import str
ImportError: No module named builtins
```

This is running under Python 2.7.6.

I suspect the error happens because `builtins` is in the standard library in Python 3 but does not exist in Python 2. I resolved it by installing the `future` package from PyPI. As for the fix in this project, I'm not sure if including `future` works flawlessly when operating under Python 3.

items.title: Does not support underscore and $ in identifiers
items.body:
The grammar for identifiers is wrong:

```
ident = ident_start:hd (letter|digit)*:tl -> ''.join([hd] + tl),

ident_start = (letter|'$'|'_'):i -> i,
```

It only allows '$' and '_' at the start, but according to [this](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Glossary/Identifier) they should be allowed afterwards too.

By the way, thanks for fixing the last issue so fast.
